04578nam a2200793Ia 9780271064314DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20162014pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710643147 a10.1515/97802710643142doi  a(DE-B1597)584054  a(OCoLC)1262307646  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aF158.44b.D38 2014eb 7aBIO0260002bisacsh04a974.8/110309222300aEmilie Davis’s Civil War :bThe Diaries of a Free Black Woman in Philadelphia, 1863–1865 /ced. by Judith Giesberg. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2016] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b24 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of People and Institutions Mentioned in the Diary -- tA Note on Method -- tIntroduction: Emilie Davis’s Civil War -- t1863 -- t1864 -- t1865 -- tCoda: All’s Well that Ends Well -- tBibliography -- tThe Memorable Days Project Editorial Team -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEmilie Davis was a free African American woman who lived in Philadelphia during the Civil War. She worked as a seamstress, attended the Institute for Colored Youth, and was an active member of her community. She lived an average life in her day, but what sets her apart is that she kept a diary. Her daily entries from 1863 to 1865 touch on the momentous and the mundane: she discusses her own and her community’s reactions to events of the war, such as the Battle of Gettysburg, the Emancipation Proclamation, and the assassination of President Lincoln, as well as the minutiae of social life in Philadelphia’s black community. Her diaries allow the reader to experience the Civil War in “real time” and are a counterpoint to more widely known diaries of the period. Judith Giesberg has written an accessible introduction, situating Davis and her diaries within the historical, cultural, and political context of wartime Philadelphia. In addition to furnishing a new window through which to view the war’s major events, Davis’s diaries give us a rare look at how the war was experienced as a part of everyday life—how its dramatic turns and lulls and its pervasive, agonizing uncertainty affected a northern city with a vibrant black community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAfrican American womenzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiavDiaries. 0aAfrican AmericanszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy19th century. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Personal Memoirs.2bisacsh  aAfrican American.  aCivil War.  aEmancipation Proclomation.  aEmile Davis.  aGiesberg.  aLincoln.  aPhiladelphia.  aThe Memorable Days Project.  aculture.  ahistory.  aunited states.  aus.  ausa.1 aGiesberg, Judith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMemorable Days Project, The, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831107452520 cprintz978027106367640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271064314?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271064314423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271064314/original  a978-3-11-074525-2  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles